You can’t guarantee nobody ever feels excluded, but you can make exclusion harder and improvement visible. Use this 30-day plan:

Week 1: Reset expectations.
Tell the team inclusion is now an operating standard, not a vibe. In your first team meeting, state 3 rules: no interrupting, no side decisions outside the room, and every affected person is included before decisions ship. Then run a short anonymous pulse survey with 4 questions: Do you feel heard, included, safe raising concerns, and positive about the team’s direction?

Week 2: Meet everyone 1:1.
Ask each person the same 4 questions: What helps you do your best work? When do you feel left out? What is one team habit that hurts morale? What should I keep, stop, and start? Do not defend the current state. Write down patterns.

Week 3: Make 2 visible fixes.
Pick the top 2 recurring issues and change them immediately. Typical examples: clearer meeting ownership, written decisions in a shared doc, rotating airtime, better handoffs, or explicit recognition of contributions. Tell the team exactly what you changed based on their input.

Week 4: Build accountability.
Add a 10-minute weekly morale/inclusion check, review workload fairness, and publicly thank specific contributions. Re-run the same pulse survey at day 30.

Success criteria by day 30: pulse scores improve, 1:1 feedback shows fewer exclusion examples, meetings have broader participation, and people can name actions you took from their feedback.

If you do only three things, do these: listen in 1:1s, fix two concrete habits fast, and show the team their feedback changed your behavior.
